In TypeScript, you can use the `as` keyword to assert a type, which effectively tells the type system "I know that in theory this value may have these multiple types, but in practice I know it will only have this one".

Here's an example:
```
let myValue: string | number;

if (/* some condition */) {
  myValue = "hello";
} else {
  myValue = 42;
}

// Use myValue as a string
console.log(myValue.length); // Okay!

// Or use myValue as a number
console.log(myValue + 1); // Okay!

myValue = myValue as string;
console.log(myValue.toUpperCase()); // Okay!
```
In this example, `myValue` is initially declared as a union type `string | number`. However, we know that based on the condition, it will only be assigned one of these types. By using the `as` keyword, we're telling TypeScript "I know that in practice, this value will only be a `string`, so treat it as such".

This is especially useful when working with APIs that return a union type, but you know that in practice, it will always return one specific type.

You can also use the `as` keyword with the `never` type to make the type system aware that a value will never take on certain types:
```
let myValue: string | number;

if (/* some condition */) {
  myValue = "hello";
} else {
  myValue = 42;
}

// Use myValue as a never type
if (myValue === "hello") {
  myValue = myValue as never; // TypeScript knows it will never be a number
  console.log(myValue.length); // Okay!
}
```
It's worth noting that using `as` can be a trade-off between type safety and convenience. By using `as`, you're effectively disabling some of TypeScript's type checking, so you need to be careful to ensure that your assumptions are correct.

